{
  "answer": "**Yama Smṛti, Chapter 1** contains the relevant declaration in verses 1.12–1.13 (YSS_1.12–1.13). These paired verses state that while individual sins have specific penances known to the wise, the convergence of all sins requires the extreme measure of adopting the skull-bowl (*kapāla*) and observing the Kāpālika vow, which is named by the wise as the ultimate penance (*paramaṃ kṛcchram*).\n\n> For each single sin that is committed, the wise know a penance; / but when all sins converge, no penance is known.[^1]  \n> When all sins converge, taking up the skull-bowl is prescribed; / that Kāpālika vow is considered its ultimate penance by the wise.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Yama Smṛti, [Chapter 1, ¶p-423161](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/01/translation/#p-423161).\n[^2]: Yama Smṛti, [Chapter 1, ¶p-22899e](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/01/translation/#p-22899e).",
